ly: Substantive Citizenship in Japan -- t11. The Construction of the ‘Native Speaker’ in Japan’s Educational Policies for TEFL -- t12. The Meaning of Japan’s Role of Professional Foreigner -- tPart 4: Native-Speakerism as a Multi-Faceted and Contemporary Social Phenomenon -- t13. Scrutinizing the Native Speaker as Referent, Entity and Project -- t14. Racialized Native Speakers: Voices of Japanese American English Language Professionals -- t15. Native-Speakerism through English-Only Policies: Teachers, Students and the Changing Face of Japan -- tPart 5: Native-Speakerism from Socio-Historical Viewpoints -- t16. Changing Perceptions? A Variationist Sociolinguistic Perspective on Native Speaker Ideologies and Standard English in Japan -- t17. Ideologies of Nativism and Linguistic Globalization -- t18. The Native Speaker Language Teacher: Through Time and Space -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe relative status of native and non-native speaker language teachers within educational institutions has long been an issue worldwide but until recently, the voices of teachers articulating their own concerns have been rare. Existing work has tended to focus upon the position of non-native teachers and their struggle against unfavourable comparisons with their native-speaker counterparts. However, more recently, native-speaker language teachers have also been placed in the academic spotlight as interest grows in language-based forms of prejudice such as ‘native-speakerism’ – a dominant ideology prevalent within the Japanese context of English language education. This innovative volume explores wide-ranging issues related to native-speakerism as it manifests itself in the Japanese and Italian educational contexts to show how native-speaker teachers can also be the targets of multifarious forms of prejudice and discrimination in the workplace.  aMode of access: Interne